on reais in 2012 and 2013, 5.56 billion reais to 6.4 billion reais in 2014, and 5.74 billion reais to 6.6 billion reais in 2015 and 2016. \u201cGiven that most of the higher guidance is concentrated in the long-end of the curve from 2014 onward, we believe the market will take some time to incorporate this new guidance into the company\u2019s share price and valuation,\u201d analysts Marcio Prado, Danilo Vitti and Maria Carolina Carneiro, at Banco Santander Brasil, wrote in a note to clients dated today.\nKlabin SA (KLBN4) (KLBN4 BS) rose 2.4 percent to 8.11 reais. Latin America \u2019s biggest paper maker was raised to the equivalent of buy at Itau BBA. Analysts cited expectations of \u201csolid earnings growth,\u201d driven in the short term by \u201chigher cost efficiency.\u201d\nBanco Santander Brasil SA (SANB11) (SANB11 BS) fell 1.1 percent to 15.87 reais. The bank\u2019s chief executive officer, Marcial Portela, said in an interview with newspaper Valor Economico today there are no negotiations under way to sell a significant minority stake in the Brazilian unit of Banco Santander SA.\nTo contact the reporter on this story: Denyse Godoy in Sao Paulo at dgodoy2@bloomberg.net\nTo contact the editor responsible for this story: David Papadopoulos at papadopoulos@bloomberg.net\n", "update_time": "2012-10-20 21:50:49", "post_time": "2012-05-30 17:24:27", "author": "Denyse Godoy", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-05-30/brazilian-stock-movers-cemig-eletrobras-and-klabin-are-active.html", "title": "Brazilian Stock Movers: Cemig, Eletrobras and Klabin Were Active", "post_date": "2012-05-30", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "IBOV", "embers_id": "d59550bdf7c542be38575745f343ffb0196b77fb"}, {"content": "Brazilian Stock Movers: Klabin, Marfrig Alimentos, QGEP, Vale\nBy Ney Hayashi - 2012-03-15T14:30:44Z\nThe following companies are having unusual price changes in Sao Paulo trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are as of 11:12 a.m. local t